d is constituted and experienced through a series of conscious acts. His fundamental concept was that of intentional consciousness. What did drag Wittgenstein into working on phenomenology? In his 'middle period' work, Wittgenstein used the headline 'Phenomenology is Grammar'. These cornerstones can be signalled by notions like language, grammar, rule, visual space versus Euclidean space, minima visibilia and colours. L. Wittgenstein's main interest takes the form of a research on language.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGrammar, Comparative and general. 0aPhenomenologyvCongresses. 0aPhenomenology. 4aLinguistik. 4aPhilosophie. 4aSprachwissenschaft. 4aWittgenstein. 4aanalytische Sprachphilosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAbreu e Silva Neto, Norberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBassols, Alejandro Tomasini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennani, Azelarabe Lahkim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenoist, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlock, Hans-Johann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnabenschuh de Porta, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Du, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemaire, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLütterfelds, W